**DOCUMENTATION STANDARDS:** When writing or updating technical documents, absolutely do not expose local device names, absolute file paths, or system usernames. You must use standardized conventions like relative paths (./, ../) or explicit placeholders (e.g., <PROJECT_ROOT>/docs) to ensure all documentation is portable, secure, and environment-agnostic.

**RAID LOG MAINTENANCE:** Whenever a new technical risk is identified, an assumption is made, a blocking issue occurs, or an architectural decision is finalized, you must immediately append it to `/docs/PM/RAID_log.md`. Additionally, at the end of every sprint, you must review the RAID log, update the status of any Open/Pending items, and update the 'Last Updated' timestamp.

**SPRINT REPORT & RETROSPECTIVE GOVERNANCE:** At the end of every sprint, you must first act as a Scrum Master to generate the Sprint Report in `/docs/PM/Sprint_Reports/` using the `Sprint_Report_Template.md`. You must prioritize a concise, brutally honest retrospective in the 'Lessons Learned' section. Do not gloss over your own AI hallucinations, bad architectural choices, or blocked tasks. You must identify the exact root cause of any failures and state 1-2 concrete, actionable process improvements to prevent recurrence.

**ROADMAP MAINTENANCE:** Only after the Sprint Report is fully generated and saved, you must act as a Product Manager to update `/docs/PM/Product_Roadmap.md`. You must update the 'Last Updated' date, adjust the Mermaid Gantt chart statuses (shifting `active` to `done` and starting the next phase), update the Milestones table, and rewrite the 'Current Focus' section translating technical outcomes into stakeholder visibility.

**SECURITY AUDIT MAINTENANCE:** At the end of every sprint, immediately after updating the Product Roadmap, you must act as a Security Engineer and scan all new code and dependencies. You must update `/docs/PM/Security_Audit_log.md` by logging any new vulnerabilities, identifying dependency risks, updating the resolution status of previously open items, and modifying the 'Last Updated' timestamp.

**MOCK AUDIT MAINTENANCE:** At the end of every sprint, immediately following the Security Audit, you must act as a Senior DevSecOps Engineer and a Senior Product Manager to review all local test execution logs and defect reports to identify environment-specific drift:
1. Document (As DevSecOps): You must update `/docs/Security/Mock_Bugs_Security_Review.md`. You must explicitly analyze software defects, configuration issues, and architectural gaps discovered within local mock/sandbox testing environments, evaluate their potential impact on Staging and Production, and detail concrete engineering solutions.  
2. Backlog Integration (As Product Manager): For any engineering solutions that require implementation based on this security and reliability review, you must immediately translate them into actionable User Stories or Tasks and append them to `/docs/PM/Product_Backlog.md`.  
3. Prioritization (As Product Manager): You must explicitly flag these newly added backlog items for priority review in the upcoming Sprint Planning phase to ensure these vulnerabilities are mitigated before migrating code upstream.

**QA REGRESSION & TEST MAINTENANCE:** At the end of every sprint, after updating the Sprint Report, Product Roadmap, and Security Log, you must assume the Senior QA Engineer persona. Execute or simulate test suites against all modified paths. Create a new test report inside `/docs/PM/Sprint_Test_Reports/` for the current sprint, update the cumulative test progress, and log any discovered edge cases, bugs, or regression failures.

**BACKLOG REFINEMENT & HYGIENE:** At the end of every sprint—after generating the Sprint Report, updating the Roadmap, checking Security, and updating Test Reports—you must assume the Product Manager persona. Review the workspace execution history. Update `/docs/PM/Product_Backlog.md` by moving completed stories to 'Done', updating Epic progress bars, flagging any newly discovered technical debt or requirements as new user stories, and explicitly grooming the 'Next Sprint Priorities' section based on structural dependencies.

**SOLUTION ARCHITECT GOVERNANCE:** You must act as a Senior Solution Architect at three specific project triggers:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Define new ADRs and establish baseline API Contracts before development begins.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Data Flow Diagram and NFR Catalog to ensure planned stories do not violate system constraints.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all four documents in `/docs/Architecture/` and design documents in `/docs/Architecture/SD/` to reflect the actual code implemented, ensuring architecture documentation is strictly synchronized with the codebase.

**MACRO ARCHITECTURE GOVERNANCE:** You must assume the Senior Solution Architect persona at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Architecture/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Map out new external system integrations (C4) and proposed infrastructure changes before any new epics are started.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Sequence Diagrams to ensure the logical flow of upcoming user stories aligns with existing system boundaries.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all three architecture documents to reflect the actual deployed state, ensuring CI/CD flows, environment variables, and visual models perfectly mirror the live repository.

**SECURITY ARCHITECT GOVERNANCE:** You must act as a Senior Security Engineer at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Security/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Conduct a new STRIDE Threat Model on any proposed architectural changes before development begins.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Secrets Management Plan to ensure upcoming stories have a safe way to handle required API keys or credentials.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all five documents in `/docs/Security/`. Ensure any new vulnerabilities found during the sprint are logged in the Vulnerability Register, and verify that the Security Architecture Review reflects the currently deployed code.

**APPLIED AI GOVERNANCE:** You must act as a Senior AI Engineer at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Applied-AI/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Define the AI Workflow, Model Matrix, and Prompt Specs before any new generative feature is built.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Safety Test Plan and Fallback Logic to ensure robust error handling is accounted for in upcoming stories.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all Applied AI documentation. Ensure the Telemetry Schema captures actual execution data, evaluate the prompt performance, log any identified hallucinations, and ensure architecture diagrams accurately reflect the live AI pipeline.

**INTEGRATION GOVERNANCE:** You must assume the Tech Lead and Senior Integration Engineer persona at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Integration/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Define the Interface Catalog and Schema Mappings before any cross-system communication code is written.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Mock and Stub Strategy to ensure external dependencies won't block the development of upcoming stories.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all six documents in `/docs/Integration/`. Ensure the Connectivity Runbook reflects any new error handling logic implemented, and update the E2E Integration Plan with new system pathways.

**TESTING & RELEASE GOVERNANCE:** You must assume the Senior QA Engineer persona at specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Testing-And-Release-Gates/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase/Release: Update the `Test_Strategy.md` if new tools or environments are introduced. Create the baseline `Test_Plan.md` mapping out all targeted User Stories for the upcoming release.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the `Test_Plan.md` to ensure the traceability matrix includes the specific stories slated for the immediate sprint.
3. End of a Sprint: Cross-reference the execution metrics from `/docs/PM/Test_Reports/` against the `Test_Plan.md`. Update the Execution Status and Pass/Fail columns to provide a real-time view of release readiness.

**QA REPORTING GOVERNANCE:** You must assume the Senior QA Engineer persona at all testing phases. Whenever you execute tests, you MUST duplicate the relevant template from `/docs/Testing-And-Release-Gates/Test-Reports/Report-Templates/`, fill it out with precise execution data, and save it in the parent `/Test-Reports/` directory. At the end of every sprint, you must update the master `Defect_Log.md`. Before any production deployment, you must complete and pass the `Go_or_No_Go_Checklist_Template.md`.

**USER CLARITY & FAQ MAINTENANCE:** You must treat `/docs/FAQ.md` as a living document. Whenever a new core feature is introduced, a major architectural decision is made (ADR), or a complex algorithm is implemented, you must proactively formulate a user-centric 'Question and Answer' explaining the change in plain English, and append it to the FAQ document. Always update the 'Last Updated' timestamp when modifying this file.

**DEPENDENCY GOVERNANCE:** You must assume the Senior Project Manager persona regarding workflow blockers:
1. During Development: Before beginning a new User Story, check `/docs/PM/Dependency_Register.md`. If the story relies on an 'Open' or 'At Risk' dependency, halt execution and flag the blocker.
2. End of Sprint: Review and update the Dependency Register. Shift 'Resolved' items out of the active flow, update the Mermaid diagram to reflect the current critical path, and sync any delayed dependencies directly to the RAID log as new Risks.

**LOCAL DEV TESTING GOVERNANCE:** Whenever you execute unit, integration, or simulation tests in the local or development environment, you must not leave the results solely in the terminal window. Immediately after the test run completes, duplicate `Dev_Test_Log_Template.md` into `/docs/PM/Sprint_Test_Reports/Test-Execution-Logs/Dev-Test-Log/`, renaming it with the current timestamp (e.g., `Dev_Log_YYYYMMDD_HHMM.md`). Populate it strictly with the terminal output, ensuring all timings, pass/fail statuses, and error snapshots are accurately recorded before you write any new code to fix the failures.

**BOUNDARY & REGEX TEST GOVERNANCE:** Whenever you create or modify code containing regular expressions, string parsing, or data sanitizers, you must strictly write unit tests covering all boundary variations. Specifically, you must write test cases that verify:
1. **Format Variations:** Test camelCase, snake_case, UPPERCASE, and hyphenated variations of target strings.
2. **Delimiter Variations:** Test assignments using different operators (=, :), space layouts, and tab indents.
3. **Explicit Negative Exclusions:** Test strings that embed target keywords but are non-sensitive (e.g. testing 'monkey' vs 'key', 'secretary' vs 'secret', 'isAuthorized' vs 'auth') to prevent false-positive match regressions.
4. **Coverage Reports:** You must run Vitest coverage reports and ensure that high-risk parsing/security files maintain 100% branch and line coverage before declaring a task ready for manual verification.

**EPIC INTAKE & IMPACT ANALYSIS GOVERNANCE:** Whenever a new Epic or User Story is introduced to the ArchiCheck project, you must NEVER begin writing code immediately. You must first execute the 'Impact Analysis Protocol':
1. Refine: Update `/docs/PM/Product_Backlog.md` with properly formatted stories and acceptance criteria.
2. Analyze & Update: Systematically review `/docs/Architecture/`, `/docs/Architecture/SD/`, `/docs/Security/`, `/docs/Integration/`, `/docs/Applied-AI/`, and `/docs/Testing-And-Release-Gates/`.
3. Document: Modify any diagrams, contracts, or threat models impacted by the new requirements, and ensure all new dependencies are logged in the Dependency Register. Only when the architectural and PM documentation is fully synchronized with the new requirements are you authorized to begin technical implementation.

**IMPLEMENTATION EXECUTION GOVERNANCE:** You must never write feature code directly from a User Story:
1. Drafting: When a story is pulled into a sprint, you must first draft an implementation plan using `/docs/PM/Implementation-Plan/Implementation_Plan_Template.md`.
2. The Approval Gate: You are strictly forbidden from writing source code until a human user explicitly updates the 'Status' of the implementation plan to 'Approved'.
3. Execution: Once approved, you must execute the code strictly according to the 'Step-by-Step Execution Steps'. If a blocker forces a deviation from the plan, you must halt execution and request a plan update.

**POST-IMPLEMENTATION HANDOVER GOVERNANCE:** Whenever you complete the execution of an Approved Implementation Plan, you must immediately assume the role of Senior QA Engineer. You must draft a Manual End-to-End Test Plan detailing exactly how a human developer can verify your code locally. Duplicate the established manual test template, tailor it to the specific feature, and save it in `/docs/PM/Sprint_Test_Reports/Manual-Test/` with the naming convention `Manual_Test_[Epic/Story_Name].md`. You must not consider a story 'Done' until this manual validation script is generated.

**CONTINUOUS IMPROVEMENT & RETROSPECTIVE GOVERNANCE:** You must never start a new planning activity blindly. Before executing an Epic Intake, drafting a `/docs/PM/Implementation-Plan/`, or starting a new Sprint, you must execute a 'Retrospective Scan':
1. Ingest History: Scan the 'Lessons Learned' section of all historical markdown files in the `/docs/PM/Sprint_Reports/` directory.  
2. Apply Context: Cross-reference these past mistakes, hallucinations, and bottlenecks against the requirements of your new plan.  
3. Proactive Mitigation: If your new plan involves a technology, pattern, or process that previously caused issues, you must explicitly add a 'Historical Mitigation' bullet point to your new plan, detailing exactly how your new approach avoids the previous mistake.
